{"title_page": "The Hedgehog Review", "text_new": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = The Hedgehog Review\n| cover = \n| editor = Jay Tolson\n| discipline = [[Cultural studies]] / [[Critical theory]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| abbreviation = Hedgehog Rev. \n| publisher = Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture<br>[[University of Virginia]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = Triannually\n| history = 1999\u2013present\n| openaccess = \n| license = \n| impact = \n| impact-year = \n| website = http://www.iasc-culture.org/THR/index.php\n| link1 = \n| link1-name = \n| link2 = \n| link2-name = \n| RSS = \n| atom = \n| JSTOR = \n| OCLC = 42747231\n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = \n| ISSN = 1527-9677\n| eISSN = 2324-867X\n| boxwidth = \n}}\n'''''The Hedgehog Review''''' is an interdisciplinary [[academic journal]] published triannually by the [[Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture]] (IASC) at the [[University of Virginia]].\n\nThe journal features [[Critical thinking|critical writing]] about [[cultural identity]], [[citizenship]], [[cultural change]], and [[cultural diversity]]. Each issue adopts a theme, which the articles address in the form of [[essay]]s, [[interview]]s, annotated [[Bibliography|bibliographies]], and the like.\n\nThe Greek lyricist [[Archilochus]] provided the inspiration for the name of the journal, when he wrote this [[aphorism]]: \"The fox knows many things, but the hedgehog knows one big thing.\" Part of the journal's mission statement is to strive \"for both the breadth of the fox and the depth of the hedgehog.\"\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.virginia.edu/iasc Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture]\n\n{{University of Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hedgehog}}\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Triannual journals]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia]]\n[[Category:Cultural journals]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{cultural-studies-journal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = The Hedgehog Review\n| cover = \n| editor = Jay Tolson\n| discipline = [[Cultural studies]] / [[Critical theory]]\n| peer-reviewed = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| abbreviation = Hedgehog Rev. \n| publisher = Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture<br>[[University of Virginia]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = Triannually\n| history = 1999 - present\n| openaccess = \n| license = \n| impact = \n| impact-year = \n| website = http://www.iasc-culture.org/THR/index.php\n| link1 = \n| link1-name = \n| link2 = \n| link2-name = \n| RSS = \n| atom = \n| JSTOR = \n| OCLC = 42747231\n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = \n| ISSN = 1527-9677\n| eISSN = 2324-867X\n| boxwidth = \n}}\n'''''The Hedgehog Review''''' is an interdisciplinary [[academic journal]] published triannually by the [[Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture]] (IASC) at the [[University of Virginia]].\n\nThe journal features [[Critical thinking|critical writing]] about [[cultural identity]], [[citizenship]], [[cultural change]], and [[cultural diversity]]. Each issue adopts a theme, which the articles address in the form of [[essay]]s, [[interview]]s, annotated [[Bibliography|bibliographies]], and the like.\n\nThe Greek lyricist [[Archilochus]] provided the inspiration for the name of the journal, when he wrote this [[aphorism]]: \"The fox knows many things, but the hedgehog knows one big thing.\" Part of the journal's mission statement is to strive \"for both the breadth of the fox and the depth of the hedgehog.\"\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.virginia.edu/iasc Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture]\n\n{{University of Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hedgehog}}\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Triannual journals]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia]]\n[[Category:Cultural journals]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{cultural-studies-journal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Changed a hyphen to an en dash.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hedgehog_Review"}
{"title_page": "Travis Denning", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Travis Denning\n| image            = \n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1992|12|1}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/travis-denning-mn0002996272/biography|title=Travis Denning biography|last=Deming|first=Mark|work=Allmusic|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|Mercury Nashville]]\n}}\n'''Travis Denning''' (born December 1, 1992) is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter signed to [[Universal Music Group Nashville]]'s [[Mercury Records|Mercury Nashville]] branch, and has charted with his singles \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\" and \"[[After a Few]]\", the latter of which has charted in the top ten on the United States [[Country Airplay]].\n\n==Musical career==\nDenning was born on December 1, 1992 in [[Warner Robins, Georgia]]. He began pursuing his musical interests after listening to music with his father as a teenager, and released his first single in 2012. After moving to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] in 2014, he got a publishing deal with RED Creative Group, which led to him writing songs for [[Jason Aldean]], [[Justin Moore]], and [[Chase Rice]] among others. After promoting himself on social media, he began performing as opening acts for Moore, Rice, and [[Lanco (band)|Lanco]]. In 2018, he signed to Mercury Nashville and released the single \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\",<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> which has charted on [[Country Airplay]].  In 2019, Denning released his second single, \"After a Few\", which became a top ten hit on the Country Airplay chart.\n\nThe song is based on Denning's real-life experiences with [[identity document forgery]] when he was underaged, and David Ashley Parker is a real person whose identity Denning used to buy beer and cigarettes when he was not old enough to do so legally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/travis-denning-david-ashley-parker/|title=Travis Denning Changes His Identity on \u2018David Ashley Parker From Powder Springs\u2019|last=Brickey|first=Kelly|date=March 31, 2018|work=Sounds Like Nashville|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref> Denning wrote the song with [[Jon Randall]] and [[Jessi Alexander]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.umgnashville.com/news/travis-denning-releases-debut-single-david-ashley-parker-powder-springs/|title=TRAVIS DENNING RELEASES DEBUT SINGLE \"DAVID ASHLEY PARKER FROM POWDER SPRINGS\"|work=Universal Music Group Nashville|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref> Denning also co-wrote [[Michael Ray (singer)|Michael Ray]]'s 2019 single \"[[Her World or Mine]]\".\n\nDenning has announced that his first [[extended play]], titled ''Beer's Better Cold'', will be released on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Drew |title=Travis Denning Announces New EP, \"Beer's Better Cold\" |url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/travis-denning-beers-better-cold-ep/ |publisher=Sounds Like Nashville |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2019, Denning began dating Madison Montgomery, who is the daughter of fellow country singer [[John Michael Montgomery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/travis-denning-five-things-to-know/|title=Five Things to Know About Travis Denning, Country's New Go-To Guy for a Good Time|last=Kruh|first=Nancy|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|work=People.com}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''Beer's Better Cold''\n* To be released: May 15, 2020\n* Label: [[Mercury Nashville]]\n* Format: [[music download]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Single\n! colspan=\"4\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Sales\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Hot Country Songs|US Country Songs]]<br /><ref name=\"BCU\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/files/pdfs/country_update_0904.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|pages=7, 16|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulletins.billboard.com/country/country_update_0218.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|date=February 18, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Country Airplay|US Country Airplay]]<br /><ref name=\"BCU\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulletins.billboard.com/country/country_update_0923.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|page=7|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2020-04-11|title=The Hot 100 Chart: April 11, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Canada Country|CAN Country]]<br><ref name=\"Canada Country\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/canada-country|title=Billboard Canada Country Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Ready for Tonight\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\"\n|  37 || 32 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[After a Few]]\"\n| 19 || 10 || 55 || 19\n|\n*US: 26,000<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Singles Sales Chart: March 2, 2020|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44155-top-30-digital-country-singles-sales-chart-march-2-2020|work=Rough Stock |date=March 4, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| ''Beer's Better Cold''\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n! Year\n! style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\"\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"After a Few\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denning, Travis}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Travis Denning\n| image            = \n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1992|12|1}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/travis-denning-mn0002996272/biography|title=Travis Denning biography|last=Deming|first=Mark|work=Allmusic|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|Mercury Nashville]]\n}}\n'''Travis Denning''' (born December 1, 1992) is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter signed to [[Universal Music Group Nashville]]'s [[Mercury Records|Mercury Nashville]] branch, and has charted with his singles \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\" and \"[[After a Few]]\", the latter of which has charted in the top ten on the United States [[Country Airplay]].\n\n==Musical career==\nDenning was born on December 1, 1992 in [[Warner Robins, Georgia]]. He began pursuing his musical interests after listening to music with his father as a teenager, and released his first single in 2012. After moving to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] in 2014, he got a publishing deal with RED Creative Group, which led to him writing songs for [[Jason Aldean]], [[Justin Moore]], and [[Chase Rice]] among others. After promoting himself on social media, he began performing as opening acts for Moore, Rice, and [[Lanco (band)|Lanco]]. In 2018, he signed to Mercury Nashville and released the single \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\",<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> which has charted on [[Country Airplay]].  In 2019, Denning released his second single, \"After a Few\", which became a top ten hit on the Country Airplay chart.\n\nThe song is based on Denning's real-life experiences with [[identity document forgery]] when he was underaged, and David Ashley Parker is a real person whose identity Denning used to buy beer and cigarettes when he was not old enough to do so legally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/travis-denning-david-ashley-parker/|title=Travis Denning Changes His Identity on \u2018David Ashley Parker From Powder Springs\u2019|last=Brickey|first=Kelly|date=March 31, 2018|work=Sounds Like Nashville|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref> Denning wrote the song with [[Jon Randall]] and [[Jessi Alexander]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.umgnashville.com/news/travis-denning-releases-debut-single-david-ashley-parker-powder-springs/|title=TRAVIS DENNING RELEASES DEBUT SINGLE \"DAVID ASHLEY PARKER FROM POWDER SPRINGS\"|work=Universal Music Group Nashville|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref> Denning also co-wrote [[Michael Ray (singer)|Michael Ray]]'s 2019 single \"[[Her World or Mine]]\".\n\nDenning has announced that his first [[extended play]], titled ''Beer's Better Cold'', will be released on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Drew |title=Travis Denning Announces New EP, \"Beer's Better Cold\" |url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/travis-denning-beers-better-cold-ep/ |publisher=Sounds Like Nashville |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2019, Denning began dating Madison Montgomery, who is the daughter of fellow country singer [[John Michael Montgomery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/travis-denning-five-things-to-know/|title=Five Things to Know About Travis Denning, Country's New Go-To Guy for a Good Time|last=Kruh|first=Nancy|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|work=People.com}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''Beer's Better Cold''\n* To be released: May 15, 2020\n* Label: [[Mercury Nashville]]\n* Format: [[music download]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Single\n! colspan=\"4\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Sales\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Hot Country Songs|US Country Songs]]<br /><ref name=\"BCU\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/files/pdfs/country_update_0904.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|pages=7, 16|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulletins.billboard.com/country/country_update_0218.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|date=February 18, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Country Airplay|US Country Airplay]]<br /><ref name=\"BCU\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulletins.billboard.com/country/country_update_0923.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update|work=Billboard|page=7|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2020-04-11|title=The Hot 100 Chart: April 11, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Canada Country|CAN Country]]<br><ref name=\"Canada Country\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/canada-country|title=Billboard Canada Country Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Ready for Tonight\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\"\n|  37 || 32 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[After a Few]]\"\n| 19 || 10 || 78 || 19\n|\n*US: 26,000<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Singles Sales Chart: March 2, 2020|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44155-top-30-digital-country-singles-sales-chart-march-2-2020|work=Rough Stock |date=March 4, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| ''Beer's Better Cold''\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n! Year\n! style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"David Ashley Parker from Powder Springs\"\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"After a Few\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denning, Travis}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Lk95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Travis_Denning"}
{"title_page": "1998\u201399 Leeds United A.F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| season             = [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]]\n| manager            = [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]] <br>''(until 1 October)''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/1225131.stm|title=From silverware to the sack | work=BBC News | date=16 March 2001}}</ref><br> [[David O'Leary]] ''(from 1 October)''\n| chairman           = [[Peter Ridsdale]]\n| stadium            = [[Elland Road]]\n| league             = [[Premier League|Premiership]]\n| league result      = [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|4th]]\n| cup1               = [[FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = [[1998\u201399 FA Cup#Fifth round|Fifth round]]\n| cup2               = [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = [[1998\u201399 Football League Cup#Fourth round|Fourth round]]\n| cup3               = [[UEFA Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup#Second round|Second round]]\n| league topscorer   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink|Hasselbaink]] (18)</span>\n| season topscorer   = <span class=\"nowrap\">Hasselbaink (20)</span>\n| highest attendance = 40,255 vs [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] <br> <small>(25 Apr 1999, [[FA Premier League|Premier League]])</small> \n| lowest attendance  = 27,561 vs [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] <br> <small>(28 Oct 1998, [[Football League Cup|League Cup]])</small>\n| average attendance = 36,028\n| prevseason         = [[1997\u201398 Leeds United A.F.C. season|1997\u201398]]\n| nextseason         = [[1999\u20132000 Leeds United A.F.C. season|1999\u20132000]]\n}}\nDuring the '[[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399 season]], Leeds United competed in the Premier League (known as the FA Carling Premiership for sponsorship reasons).\n\n==Season summary==\nLeeds were expected to progress once more under manager George Graham after the former Arsenal manager guided Leeds to 5th place in his first full season in charge, Graham had added to his squad signing defender Danny Granville and dutch striker Clyde Winjard and after just 4 games Leeds went top of the Premiership for the first time in their history but rumours then begun of George Graham taking the Tottenham job after Spurs had sacked Christian Gross, the saga dragged on when finally after a UEFA cup game against Maritimo of Portugal Graham indeed left Leeds for Tottenham, Grahams assistant David O'leary took charge while Leeds attempted to attract Leicester boss Martin O'Neil (who eventually refused) but United performances on the pitch begun improving -despite only drawing several games, many teenage players were given debuts by O'Leary and put in great performances including against Italian giants Roma in the UEFA cup although Leeds were knocked out, needless to say O'Leary was appointed manager in time for the game against Derby which ended 2-2, Leeds then begun winning regularly playing impressive attacking football with several talented youngsters including goal keeper Paul Robinson, defenders Ian Harte, Johnathan Woodgate, Mid fielders Lee Bowyer (who was signed from Charlton 2 seasons before) Steven McPhail, along with strikers Alan Smith and Harry Kewell but David O'leary was eager bring in experienced players to add to this young team and signed David Batty from Newcastle, Batty was a key player in the Leeds side that won the old division 1 title in 1992 and a fans favourite, in the run up to X mas Leeds were almost in contention for a shot at the title but in the new year suffered back to back losses against Southampton and Newcastle which ended any league-winning hopes and were also knocked out of the FA cup, despite this Leeds ended the season in red hot form setting a record of 7 straight wins and a 1-0 victory over Arsenal which cost the gunners the title race, Leeds finished an impressive 4th place in the league -they're highest finish yet and with one of the most exiting young squads in the country the future certainly looked bright for United.\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1998\u201399 FA Premier League}}\n{{:1998\u201399 FA Premier League|showteam=LEE}}\n\n;Results summary\n{{Fb_rs|hw=12|hd=5|hl=2|hgf=32|hga=9|aw=6|ad=8|al=5|agf=30|aga=25}}\n{{Fb_rs_footer|s=[http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=115 1998-99 FA Premier League table]|date=September 2015}}\n\n;Results by round\n{{#invoke:sports rbr table|table|legendpos=b\n|header=Round\n|label1= Ground\n| res1=A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/H/A/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/H/H/A/H/A/A/H/A\n|label2= Result\n| res2=D/W/D/W/D/D/D/L/D/D/D/W/W/W/L/W/W/L/W/D/L/W/L/L/W/W/W/W/W/W/W/D/D/D/W/L/W/D\n|label3= Position\n| res3=6/7/5/1/3/5/5/10/9/10/9/6/5/5/6/3/3/5/4/5/5/5/5/6/5/5/4/4/4/3/4/4/4/4/4/4/4/4\n<!-- -->\n|text_H=Home|text_A=Away\n|color_W=green2|text_W=Win\n|color_D=yellow2|text_D=Draw\n|color_L=red2|text_L=Loss\n|color_1=1st|color_2=2nd|color_3=3rd|color_18-=red1\n\n|source=[http://www.11v11.com/teams/leeds-united/tab/matches/season/1999 11v11.com: 1998-99 Leeds United results]\n|date=September 2015\n}}\n\n==Results==\n''Leeds United's score comes first''<ref>http://www.statto.com/football/teams/leeds-united/1998-1999/results</ref>\n\n===Legend===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"background-color: #d0ffe3;\"|<small>Win</small>\n|style=\"background-color: #ffffdd;\"|<small>Draw</small>\n|style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;\"|<small>Loss</small>\n|}\n\n===FA Premier League===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center\"\n!Date!!Opponent!!Venue!!Result!!Attendance!!Scorers\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffffdd;\"\n| 15 August 1998 ||[[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]||A||0\u20130||34,162||\n|-style=\"backgro