 = [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|4th]]\n| cup1               = [[FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = [[1998\u201399 FA Cup#Fifth round|Fifth round]]\n| cup2               = [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = [[1998\u201399 Football League Cup#Fourth round|Fourth round]]\n| cup3               = [[UEFA Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup#Second round|Second round]]\n| league topscorer   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink|Hasselbaink]] (18)</span>\n| season topscorer   = <span class=\"nowrap\">Hasselbaink (20)</span>\n| highest attendance = 40,255 vs [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] <br> <small>(25 Apr 1999, [[FA Premier League|Premier League]])</small> \n| lowest attendance  = 27,561 vs [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] <br> <small>(28 Oct 1998, [[Football League Cup|League Cup]])</small>\n| average attendance = 36,028\n| prevseason         = [[1997\u201398 Leeds United A.F.C. season|1997\u201398]]\n| nextseason         = [[1999\u20132000 Leeds United A.F.C. season|1999\u20132000]]\n}}\nDuring the '[[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399 season]], Leeds United competed in the Premier League (known as the FA Carling Premiership for sponsorship reasons).\n\n==Season summary==\nLeeds were expected to progress once more under manager George Graham after the former Arsenal manager guided Leeds to 5th place in his first full season in charge, Graham had added to his squad signing defender Danny Granville and dutch striker Clyde Winjard and after just 4 games Leeds went top of the Premiership for the first time in their history but rumours then begun of George Graham taking the Tottenham job after Spurs had sacked Christian Gross, the saga dragged on when finally after a UEFA cup game against Maritimo of Portugal Graham indeed left Leeds for Tottenham, Grahams assistant David O'leary took charge while Leeds attempted to attract Leicester boss Martin O'Neil (who eventually refused) but United performances on the pitch begun improving -despite only drawing several games, many teenage players were given debuts by O'Leary and put in great performances including against Italian giants Roma in the UEFA cup although Leeds were knocked out, needless to say O'Leary was appointed manager in time for the game against Derby which ended 2-2, Leeds then begun winning regularly playing impressive attacking football with several talented youngsters including goal keeper Paul Robinson, defenders Ian Harte, Johnathan Woodgate, Mid fielders Lee Bowyer (who was signed from Charlton 2 seasons before) Steven McPhail, along with strikers Alan Smith and Harry Kewell but David O'leary was eager bring in experienced players to add to this young team and singed David Batty from Newcastle, Batty was a key player in the Leeds side that won the old division 1 title in 1992 and a fans favourite, in the run up to X mas Leeds were almost in contention for a shot at the title but in the new year suffered back to back losses against Southampton and Newcastle which ended any league-winning hopes and were also knocked out of the FA cup, despite this Leeds ended the season in red hot form setting a record of 7 straight wins and a 1-0 victory over Arsenal which cost the gunners the title race, Leeds finished an impressive 4th place in the league -they're highest finish yet and with one of the most exiting young squads in the country the future certainly looked bright for United.\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1998\u201399 FA Premier League}}\n{{:1998\u201399 FA Premier League|showteam=LEE}}\n\n;Results summary\n{{Fb_rs|hw=12|hd=5|hl=2|hgf=32|hga=9|aw=6|ad=8|al=5|agf=30|aga=25}}\n{{Fb_rs_footer|s=[http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=115 1998-99 FA Premier League table]|date=September 2015}}\n\n;Results by round\n{{#invoke:sports rbr table|table|legendpos=b\n|header=Round\n|label1= Ground\n| res1=A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/H/A/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/H/H/A/H/A/A